               <head>Grant; Gazeley, etc.; 1299</head>
               <msContents>
                  <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  <msItem>
                     <p>
                        <placeName key="place_111660">Gazeley</placeName>.
                        <origDate when="1299">1299</origDate>. 
                        Grant from <persName>
                           <forename>William</forename> 
                           <surname>Sperling</surname> of <placeName role="person" key="place_111667">Needham Street (Nedham)</placeName>
                        </persName> to <persName>
                           <forename>John</forename> 
                           <surname>Fiss</surname>
                        </persName> and <persName nymRef="Fiss">
                           <forename>Sarra</forename> his wife</persName>, for a certain sum of money, of an acre of arable land called "le Doune" in the fields of <placeName key="place_111663">Higham (Heyham)</placeName>, of which half an acre lies between the land late of <persName>
                           <forename>Alan</forename> 
                           <surname>(the Reaper) 'Messor'</surname>
                        </persName> and that of <persName>
                           <forename>John</forename> 
                           <surname>Aleyn</surname>
                        </persName> abutting on 'le Feldwoye' [sic] and on the land of the <orgName role="abbot">abbot of St Osilth</orgName>; and the other half acre between the lands of <persName>
                           <forename>Ralph</forename> le <surname>Neweman</surname>
                        </persName> and <persName>
                           <forename>Richard</forename> 
                           <surname>Proudfot</surname></persName>.
                        Dated at <placeName role="date" key="place_111660">Gazeley (Gaysle)</placeName> on Friday (9 Oct) after the feast of St Faith Virgin 27 Edward I (1299).
                     Witnesses. <persName>
                           <forename>Thomas</forename> 
                           <surname>Passelewe</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Walter</forename> le <surname>Mercer</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Alexander</forename> 
                           <surname>Baston</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Walter</forename> de la <surname>Kersonere</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>William</forename> 
                           <surname>Sparke</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Thomas</forename> 
                           <surname type="patronymic">son of 'Fabr'</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Henry</forename> le <surname>Beusler</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Richard</forename> 
                           <surname>(the Cowherd) 'Vaccario'</surname></persName>, <persName>
                           <forename>Roger</forename> the <surname>clerk</surname></persName>, and others. 
                     The seal is wanting.
                     </p>
                  </msItem>
